# TypeScript Standards

## Error Handling

```typescript
// BAD - silent catch
try {
  await fetchData();
} catch (e) {}

// GOOD - log and rethrow or handle
try {
  await fetchData();
} catch (e) {
  logger.error('Failed to fetch', { error: e });
  throw new DataFetchError('Unable to retrieve data', { cause: e });
}
```

- Never use empty catch blocks. At minimum log the error.
- Prefer custom error classes for domain errors.
- Use `cause` when wrapping errors (Node 16+).

## Type Safety

- Avoid `any`. Use `unknown` and narrow with type guards when type is uncertain.
- Prefer `interface` for object shapes; use `type` for unions, intersections, or mapped types.
- Use `strict: true` (or equivalent) and fix resulting errors.
- Annotate function return types for public APIs and non-obvious returns.
- No implicit `any`.
- No `@ts-nocheck`.
- No non-null assertions (`!`).
- Guard nested property reads:
  - Use null guards / optional chaining (`user?.name`) instead of `user.name`.

## Async / Await

- Use `async/await` over raw Promises for readability.
- Await in parallel when independent: `const [a, b] = await Promise.all([fetchA(), fetchB()]);`
- Do not mix `.then()` and `await` in the same flow; pick one style.

## Null and Undefined

- Prefer optional chaining (`obj?.prop`) and nullish coalescing (`??`) over manual checks when appropriate.
- Use explicit `| null` or `| undefined` in types when the value can be absent.

## Async Cancellation (non-UI)

- For `fetch` and other cancelable async work, prefer `AbortController` where applicable.
- If you catch cancellation errors, handle them intentionally:
  - Treat `AbortError` (and equivalent) as an expected cancellation signal.
  - Do not swallow non-cancellation errors silently—log and rethrow or convert to a domain error.
- Ensure cleanup for long-lived async work (timers, streams, subscriptions) so resources are released deterministically.

